03885nam a22005655i 9780804796699DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047966997 a10.1515/97808047966992doi  a(DE-B1597)563896  a(OCoLC)1198930108  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPHI0180002bisacsh04a833/.9122231 aNorth, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Yield :bKafka's Atheological Reformation /cPaul North. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (400 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMeridian: Crossing Aesthetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tConversations -- tPreface -- tA Note on References -- tAbbreviations -- t§ Introduction -- t§ Refutation of What Being Never Was -- t§ Better Weapons than Faith and Hope -- t§ Excursus: For a Kafkan Logic -- t§ The Problem of Our Art -- t§ The Yield: On Forgoing Power -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Yield is a once-in-a-generation reinterpretation of the oeuvre of Franz Kafka. At the same time, it is a powerful new entry in the debates about the supposed secularity of the modern age. Kafka is one of the most admired writers of the last century, but this book presents us with a Kafka few will recognize. It does so through a fine-grained analysis of the three hundred "thoughts" the writer penned near the end of World War I, when he had just been diagnosed with tuberculosis. Since they were discovered after Kafka's death, the meaning of the so-called "Zürau aphorisms" has been open to debate. Paul North's elucidation of what amounts to Kafka's only theoretical work shows them to contain solutions to problems Europe has faced throughout modernity. Kafka offers responses to phenomena of violence, discrimination, political repression, misunderstanding, ethnic hatred, fantasies of technological progress, and the subjugation of the worker, among other problems. Reflecting on secular modernity and the theological ideas that continue to determine it, he critiques the ideas of sin, suffering, the messiah, paradise, truth, the power of art, good will, and knowledge. Kafka's controversial alternative to the bad state of affairs in his day? Rather than fight it, give in. Developing some of Kafka's arguments, The Yield describes the ways that Kafka envisions we can be good by "yielding" to our situation instead of striving for something better.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 4aAtheology. 4aHeidegger. 4aJewishness. 4aOntology. 4aPhenomenology. 4aTheology. 4aZionism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479669940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804796699423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804796699.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles